Hi Steve,  I hope you are doing well.  I took a brief look at your LI profile and it occurred to me that we could, maybe, join forces in the processing field with regards to the optimization of aggregates processing plants. I‚Äôve developed AggXtream¬Æ, a stochastic and dynamic simulator of crushing and sand washing circuits, which has been built with the modern phenomenological (PBM ‚Äì Population Balance Model) and empirical mathematical models of crushing, screening and classification currently available. These features, along with AggXtream‚Äôs sensitivity analysis capabilities and its internal optimization engine, allow for the simulation of thousands of scenarios in no time, making the outlining of optimization strategies and debottlenecking of processing plants with complex interactions a truly feasible task from the simulation perspective.  The basic inputs for an AggXtream modelling and simulation project are: list of equipment, tonnages and gradations from one or more (preferably) sampling campaigns and operating constraints. Standard outputs are: model of the crushing / washing circuit with flow-sheet and mass balance (per size fraction), along with the results from sensitivity analyses (factorial experiments). Circuit optimization exercises can also be carried out whenever objective functions are specified, e.g. maximization of a certain gradation, w.r.t. operating constraints. The results from the factorial experiments can be overwhelming (+1K combinations of operating variables), so I frequently sum them up in graphics that, together, comprise what I call PPMs ‚Äì Plant Performance Maps.  In the case of plants with an automatic control system in place, AggXteam‚Äôs Rule Finder can be employed to summarize the outputs from the sensitivity analyses into if-then rules that can be seamlessly embedded into the control system as part/whole of an expert control system.  Due to the severe (almost 5 years now...) crisis in the construction market in Brazil, I came up with the idea of looking for partners to take AggXtream abroad, using it as a tool to reach conclusions and outline optimization strategies that would be difficult to find otherwise.  I‚Äôve taken the liberty of forwarding you a copy of one of my LinkedIn posts and a ppt about AggXtream, should you be interested in learning more about it and continuing our conversation.  Many thanks!  Best regards, Octavio

I‚Äôve taken the liberty of forwarding you a copy of one of my LinkedIn posts and a flyer about AggXtream, should you be interested in learning more about it and continuing our conversation. The basic inputs for an AggXtream modelling and simulation project are: list of equipment, tonnages and gradations from one or more (preferably) sampling campaigns and operating constraints. Standard outputs are: model of the crushing / washing circuit with flowsheet and mass balance (per size fraction), along with the results from sensitivity analyses (factorial experiments). Circuit optimization exercises can also be carried out whenever objective functions are specified, e.g. maximisation of a certain gradation, w.r.t. operating constraints. The results from the factorial experiments can be overwhelming (+1K combinations of operating variables), so I frequently sum them up in graphics that, together, comprise what I call PPMs ‚Äì Plant Performance Maps. In the case of plants which an automatic control system in place, AggXteam‚Äôs Rule Finder can be employed to summarize the outputs from the sensitivity analyses into if-then rules that can be seamlessly embedded into the control system as part/whole of an expert control system. Our business model is to join forces with our partners, using AggXtream as a tool to reach conclusions and outline optimization strategies that would be difficult to find otherwise. Hi Erik, thanks. You are right indeed: the site is horrendous! Jesus... Well, as far as I could understand from what's available in their website, QuarryVision is no more than a set of sensors (tonnages, gradations, stoppages) installed in selected streams / locations of a circuit comprising a supervisory control system. Although they claim their system performs optimization and debottlenecking tasks automatically, there is no clear indication on how these could be achieved by the system as-is without heavy human intervention. Long story short, it's a supervisory control system, probably a good one, although the design is, is my opinion, quite old-fashioned. Their analyses rely heavily on historical data and (maybe) basic regulatory PID loops, e.g. for the control of tonnages and bin levels. Our approach with AggXtream has more to do with what is in their "Every Quarry Has a Heartbeat (come on, guys...)" section,  under "Advanced Analytics Application & Support (Optional)", nevertheless with a much superior approach, since a Bedrock's AggFlow flowsheet is not a model of a plant but rather a mass-balance exercise (Bedrock tried to overcome this with that infamous bucket feature, but still not a model of a circuit). With AggXtream, a mathematical model of the circuit, built and calibrated periodically against plant data, could be embedded into the system, thus serving not only as a reliable performance benchmark but also, and most importantly, as a feed-forward, expert control system that would then assure that the PID loops would be doing their best to control tonnages and bin levels at an optimal configuration of the whole circuit, and here is where cost-effective optimization strategies found with AggXtream shine.  Best regards, Octavio

CONTENT: Hi Liberty, I got your calls later on, but couldn't answer them because I was driving. I've been in the aggregates business for more than 15 years; most of the time in the frontline, managing operations, but more recently I've been consolidating a move towards operating performance enhancement by means of modeling & simulation projects for crushing and screening systems, combined with the development of advanced control strategies for such systems. I have developed some tools and a - in my opinion - awesome modeling and simulation software to help me out with those, so I want to see how far I can go with this personal project. Long story short, I have step back from the frontline, and I understand from your last email that this is not the profile you are seeking right now. What a pity; it would be nice to work in Canada... I wish you every success in finding a good professional to this job. Best regards, Octavio

This Masterclass demystifies creative intelligence, and explores practical approaches to harness the creativity of individuals, teams and organizations towards higher levels of engagement, effectiveness and competitiveness.


Current and future leaders are increasingly expected to complement their technical skills and know-how with creativity and intuition. This enables them to steer their ships towards a desirable and thriving future while navigating uncertainty and ambiguity. At the same time organizations must learn to harness organizational creativity as a powerful lever against imitability, and as a key enabler for sustainable growth. 


Creativity is not about art or music. Creativity is an intelligence, and a distinguishing characteristic of humanity. Creativity is our limitless capacity to dream and to create future possibilities previously unimagined. Creativity is play, it is perspective, it is beginner‚Äôs eyes. Most importantly, creativity is a process that can be learnt and enhanced.


Agenda


Wednesday, September 18th, 2019 at 19:30 hrs.

MasterClass "Creative Intelligence in the 4th Industrial Revolution "

About the speaker


Dr. Yazan Hijazi holds a PhD in Electrical Engineering with extensive experience leading multi-million-dollar projects resulting in propriety technologies for the US Air Force, Seagate Technologies, and the US Nuclear Safety Agency. Over the course of 20 years he assumed roles of scientist, professor, executive director, entrepreneur and advisor across several industry verticals. His expertise converges at the intersection of technology, business innovation and human potential. His mission is to support individuals illuminate their creative greatness, and to help organizations unlock and sustain competitive advantage by operationalizing innovation and activating the Human Element. 


Dr. Hijazi is currently director of Innovation & Entrepreneurship at Al-Hussein Technical University (HTU) in Amman, Jordan; he is a visiting professor at IE University in Madrid, Spain and runs a human development and innovation advisory firm called Human Engineering servicing clients worldwide.
